        "header": "3Task Formulation",
        "images": [
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2604.13151/2604.13151v1/x3.png",
                "caption": "Figure 2:Illustration of the LM agent traversing the 2D grid map to achieve the goal given by the task DAG. In each timestep, the environment returns the set of admissible moves and the information about the task node, if discovered. The LM agent must retain relevant information about the map geometry, the task DAG structure and the states of the discovered nodes to achieve the goal node.",
                "position": 352
            },
            {
                "img": "https://arxiv.org/html/2604.13151/2604.13151v1/x4.png",
                "caption": "Figure 3:Three illustrative examples demonstrating edge cases. In all three maps, node A is achieved and node B is pending, so the agent can traverse back to B, or explore to discover node C. The purple dashed line depicts the path the LM agent has taken, and the blue transparent line denotes a potentially more optimal path. In Figure3a, the LM agent can infer the shortest path to node A and traverse unseen nodes as part of an exploitation strategy. In contrast, in Figure3b, the agent has already taken the shortest path from node B to node A. Hence, it may be more optimal to make a short detour and observe 5 unseen cells at the cost of a short detour. Figure3c illustrates a case where target cells𝒯​(t)\\mathcal{T}(t)are placed symmetrically. Here gain will always be 1 for all four actions. A metric solely relying on gain cannot penalize the LM agent wandering indefinitely in the red dotted region.",
                "position": 355
            }
        ]
    },
